books.title: The Unwritten, Vol. 1: Tommy Taylor and the Bogus Identity
books.author: Mike Carey, Bill Willingham, Peter Gross, Yuko Shimizu

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of The Unwritten, Vol. 1: Tommy Taylor and the Bogus Identity: Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
The Unwritten, like its spiritual comic-book little sister Fable, is, in many ways, a writer's story about writing. As a result it is in love with the stories of storytelling and it wants its readers to be in love with storytelling as well.

Taking the power of stories from where others usually leave off, it empowers the modern myths of our time with a life of their own and lets them take off.

The result seems to be an almost-John Gardner-like graphic novel on how to best explore stories. Clever, well-written, and worth reading.

books.title: The Unwritten, Vol. 2: Inside Man
books.author: Mike Carey, Peter Gross, Yuko Shimizu

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of The Unwritten, Vol. 2: Inside Man: Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
Vol 2 picks up where Vol 1 left off and accelerates. Everything continues, only more so and the prose moves to greater heights, with a number of the lines seeming almost axiomatic despite their originality.

Few comics can accomplish quotability, as the words are so tightly tied to the images, but without losing the connection, Vol 2 can count itself among the few.

GoodReads Review of Atta: Rating - 5/5
reviews.content:
Atta is a book that is hard to describe. Meticulous, fascinating, disturbing.

In some ways it might be best to go into this book with no knowledge of what is within, which is how I did it. To be so thoroughly introduced to the internal voice and thought process of a character who is often used to exemplify inhumanity, and whose acts are well deserving of revilement, is to repudiate dehumanization, generalization and demonization. Even our worst enemies are still people; their thoughts and motivations are not uniform, and may not even be what we suspect. Even the clearest of evils does not have the clearest of sources.

Jarett Kobek writes a well-researched historical fiction from the point of view of one of the 9/11 plane hijackers, centered on the idea that for Atta the attack was as much an architectural statement as a religious one. Few books will make you think more.

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of Stranger Things Happen: Rating - 4/5
reviews.content:
In Kelly Link's collection of short stories, names get mixed up, settings change, tenses switch, tales are familiar yet new and emotions soak into you slowly, with the help of odd metaphors. Things that should make sense don't and the parts that shouldn't make sense are perfectly clear.

In a strange and utterly unique way, Link has captured dreams and put them down on paper in their perfect dream logic.

books.title: The Wizard Lord (The Annals of the Chosen, #1)
books.author: Lawrence Watt-Evans

reviews.title: GoodReads Review of Superpowers: Rating - 3/5
reviews.content:
This book starts well and from the moment the World Trade Center is mentioned the general flow is pretty well established. There are few surprises here, and the question of what the book's heroes would do on 9/11 pulls through some mediocre prose and overdone foreshadowing.

However, at about 3/4ths through the book, something happens. The characters gain depth. As soon as you hit that, the book becomes almost impossible to put down. You now care about the once relatively shallow superheroes. The fact that you know what is to come doesn't change the fact that you now really want to know what is going to happen to them. Unfortunately, though the ending ties everything up, it feels somewhat lackluster.

The book is decent overall, however, it feels as if the characters' depth is almost an accident. However, if you like stories about Superheroes you should pick this book up.
